<main>
  <div class="article-content">

    <p>The Miracle Question is a 13-word evangelism opener: <strong>"If God could do a miracle in your life, what would it be?"</strong> It starts a natural Gospel conversation with anyone, anywhere, without being pushy, weird, or preachy. It works because it doesn't lead with doctrine — it leads with need. And everyone has a need.</p>

    <p>This is Step 1 of the <a href="/evangelism">Story Evangelism Process</a> — field-tested across six continents and 25+ years of frontline missions by RK Castillo. It's the question that has opened thousands of doors that argument and debate never could.</p>

    <h2>What Is the Miracle Question?</h2>

    <p>The Miracle Question is defined as a single conversational question designed to invite anyone — believer or not — to tell you what they need from God. The question is: <em>"If God could do a miracle in your life, what would it be?"</em></p>

    <p>Those 13 words do something remarkable. They position God as the solution before you've said anything theological. They give the other person complete control over the conversation. And they create a natural, respectful opening to pray — right there, on the spot.</p>

    <p>Most people will answer it. Even people who don't follow Jesus, even skeptics, even people who say they don't believe in God — because most people have something they wish were different. Pain, fear, a broken relationship, a desperate situation. The Miracle Question invites them to name it out loud in the context of what God could do.</p>

    <h2>Why Does the Miracle Question Work?</h2>

    <p>Three reasons set the Miracle Question apart from every other evangelism opener.</p>

    <h3>It's not a debate</h3>
    <p>When you lead with theology, people defend their worldview. When you ask someone what they need, they open up. The Miracle Question meets people in their need — not where you want them to be. No one feels attacked by it. No one feels judged. It's just a genuine question from someone who actually cares.</p>

    <h3>It positions God as the source before anything is explained</h3>
    <p>Before a single Bible verse is quoted, the person is already thinking: <em>what would God do for me?</em> That's a powerful mental shift. They're no longer thinking about religion, church, or doctrine. They're thinking about a God who could change their situation.</p>

    <h3>It leads directly to prayer — and prayer is where God shows up</h3>
    <p>Once someone answers, you have permission to pray. More people come to Jesus through experiencing the power of God than through hearing an argument for Christianity. The Miracle Question opens the door to that experience immediately.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>During a COVID Easter campaign, RK's team received over 1,000 prayer requests in four days using this exact approach on Facebook. The Miracle Question works online, in person, with strangers, and with friends.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>How Do You Use the Miracle Question?</h2>

    <p>The process is straightforward. Here are the five steps:</p>

    <div class="process-steps">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Ask the Question</h3>
          <p>Say it naturally, not robotically. "Hey, can I ask you something kind of random? If God could do a miracle in your life, what would it be?" Look them in the eye. Mean it. You actually want to know.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Listen Without Interrupting</h3>
          <p>Let them answer completely. Don't rush to pray. Don't start explaining the Gospel. Just listen — because what they say tells you exactly how to pray and exactly what story to tell.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Pray Short, Direct, and in Command Form</h3>
          <p>Don't ask God "if it's Your will." His will is already established. Pray with authority: "Pain, go. Body, be healed. In Jesus' name. Amen." Short. Bold. Done. Then stop talking and let God work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Re-Interview</h3>
          <p>Ask: "How does that feel right now?" You're not checking whether God did something — you're giving God room to report what He already did. Many people notice changes in the moment. Pay attention to what they say.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h3>Share Your Jesus Story</h3>
          <p>Whether or not something visible happened, move into your story. Two words for before. One sentence on why you chose to follow Jesus. Two words for after. Then ask: "What do you think about Jesus?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What Happens After Someone Answers?</h2>

    <p>The moment someone answers the Miracle Question, the conversation shifts. They've just told you what they need most. Now your job is to connect their need to a God who actually moves.</p>

    <p>Pray directly, not passively. "Lord, if it be Your will…" is not a prayer of faith — it's an escape hatch. Jesus never prayed that way when healing people. He commanded. He spoke. He acted on the authority He had been given. You have the same Spirit. Pray the same way.</p>

    <p>Then re-interview. "How does that feel?" is one of the most powerful sentences in the Miracle Question process. It creates a moment of reflection where the person notices whether something changed. Even small changes — a sense of peace, a reduction in pain, a feeling of being cared for — are openings for the Gospel.</p>

    <p>From there, share your story. Not a systematic theology. Two phrases before, one sentence on the decision, two phrases after. You're not preaching a sermon — you're telling a friend about the most important relationship in your life. That's always more compelling than an argument.</p>

    <h2>Does the Miracle Question Work in Any Culture?</h2>

    <p>Yes. RK has used this approach on six continents — Latin America, Southeast Asia, Western Europe, Africa, North America, and Australia. Every culture has pain. Every person has something they wish God would change. The Miracle Question works because it's not asking about religion. It's asking about need — and need is universal.</p>

    <p>It works in secular cultures because you're not leading with church language or Bible verses. It works in religious cultures because you're affirming that God hears and answers prayer. It works in hostile cultures because no one can tell you not to care about what someone needs.</p>

    <p>The only adjustment is tone. In some cultures you go slower. In others you're more direct. But the question itself travels everywhere.</p>

    <h2>Where Does the Miracle Question Fit in the Bigger Process?</h2>

    <p>The Miracle Question is Step 1 of the Story Evangelism Process — the complete field-tested evangelism framework that moves from a stranger to a new worker in a single conversation. Here's the full sequence:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Step 1 — Miracle Question:</strong> Open the conversation with need</li>
      <li><strong>Step 2 — Pray for the Miracle:</strong> Short, direct, in command form</li>
      <li><strong>Step 3 — 2 Phrase 2:</strong> Your Jesus story in five sentences or less</li>
      <li><strong>Step 4 — Who Is Jesus?</strong> Your favorite conversation — not religion, but your friend</li>
      <li><strong>Step 5 — Good Bad Give Go:</strong> Creation was Good, sin brought Bad, Jesus Gave His life, now we Go</li>
      <li><strong>Step 6 — Why Who How:</strong> Invite them in, get five names, send them out today</li>
      <li><strong>Step 7 — 7 Stories of Hope:</strong> The seven stories every new believer needs to know</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The Miracle Question is the door. Everything else is what you do after the door is open. Learning to <a href="/discipleship">disciple the people who respond</a> is the next critical step — because the goal is not a decision, it's a Worker.</p>

    <h2>What If Someone Says No or Pushes Back?</h2>

    <p>Some people will shrug. Some will say they don't believe in miracles. Some will get suspicious and wonder if you're selling something. That's fine — the Miracle Question is an opener, not a guarantee.</p>

    <p>If someone says "I don't really believe in that stuff," respond with curiosity: <em>"No problem. If you could change one thing about your life right now, what would it be?"</em> Same question. Different frame. You're looking for the Person of Peace — the person God has already prepared who is ready to receive. The Miracle Question helps you find them faster. Not everyone will respond, and that's okay. Move on, stay warm, keep asking.</p>

    <p>Rejection is not failure. RK teaches that rejection is a reward — Jesus said in Luke 6 that those rejected for His sake have a great reward in heaven. When you embrace the possibility of a no, the fear disappears. And when the fear disappears, you start asking everyone.</p>

  </div>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Common Questions About the Miracle Question</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What is the Miracle Question in evangelism?</h3>
      <p>The Miracle Question is a 13-word evangelism opener: "If God could do a miracle in your life, what would it be?" It starts a natural, non-confrontational Gospel conversation by inviting someone to share their deepest need, then creates an immediate opportunity to pray and introduce Jesus.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>How do you respond after someone answers the Miracle Question?</h3>
      <p>Pray for them right there — short, direct, and in command form. Then ask "How does that feel right now?" Whether or not something visible happens, move into your Jesus story: two words for before you followed Jesus, a sentence about why you chose to follow Him, and two words for what changed after.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Does asking about miracles feel pushy or weird?</h3>
      <p>No — and that's what makes the Miracle Question so effective. You're not declaring a theological position or asking someone to agree with anything. You're simply asking what someone needs. Most people respond warmly to someone who genuinely cares about what they're going through.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Can anyone use the Miracle Question, or do you have to be an evangelist?</h3>
      <p>Anyone can use it. Jesus said in Mark 16 that signs would follow those who believe — not a special class of ministers, but everyday believers. The Miracle Question requires no special training, title, or gift. It just requires showing up and asking.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What if someone says they don't believe in miracles?</h3>
      <p>Reframe the question: "No problem — if you could change one thing about your life right now, what would it be?" The goal is to find the Person of Peace — someone God has already prepared to receive. Not everyone will respond, and that's fine. Keep asking.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

